{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d75b24d6-f9a8-4a9d-bf5d-3b314b8f01d7","content":"\n\nHere's the mapping from VSTest → Microsoft.Testing.Platform flags:\n\n| VSTest (`dotnet test`) | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` | `--filter \"Category=Integration\"` |\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**New command:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project <TestProject> -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n\n- On .NET 8 SDK, `dotnet test` still routes through VSTest by default. Use `dotnet run --project ... --` (or the built executable directly) to invoke the new platform.\n- You'll need these NuGet packages in the test project: `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump`.\n- If you later move to .NET 9+ SDK, you can switch back to `dotnet test` by setting `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in your project, and the new flags work directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b8ed792-9768-4d28-a4c4-7a6f13d43924","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating a `dotnet test` command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing infrastructure, not a code change in the repo. Let me provide the answer directly.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n1. `--filter` → `--filter` (same, but the flag is supported)\n2. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` \n3. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n4. `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n\n\n5. `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n6. `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nI should clarify that with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the invocation method matters—you can either use `dotnet test` as a wrapper or run the test executable directly, and the flag syntax varies depending on which approach you take. Starting with .NET 9 SDK, `dotnet test` has deeper integration with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, which affects how these arguments are passed through.\n\nFor .NET 8 specifically, the more common pattern is to build the test project and run it as an executable directly, passing the platform-specific flags like `--filter`, `--report-trx`, `--coverage`, `--crashdump`, and `--hangdump` with their respective timeout values. The exact command structure depends on whether you're using `dotnet run` to invoke the test project or running the compiled executable directly. I'm mapping out how the VSTest flags translate to Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents, and each one requires a specific NuGet package to work properly. Since .NET 8 doesn't natively support the new platform through `dotnet test`, I'll need to either run the test executable directly or use `dotnet run` instead.","outputTokens":1306},"id":"0deedcb7-bbbf-4f70-9a95-5cfba4675012","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:49:24.257Z","parentId":"961677e6-9897-4131-a4ac-6cf963f20820"}
